# Dependency injection
If you prefer to define resilience pipelines using IServiceCollection, you'll need to install the Polly.Extensions package:

```text
dotnet add package Polly.Extensions
```

then you can define your resilience pipeline as shown:

```C#
var services = new ServiceCollection();

ResiliencePipeline pipelineToAdd = new ResiliencePipelineBuilder()
    .AddRetry(new RetryStrategyOptions())
    .AddTimeout(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10))
    .Build();

// Define a resilience pipeline with the name "my-pipeline"
services.AddKeyedSingleton<ResiliencePipeline>("my-pipeline", pipelineToAdd);

// Build the service provider
var serviceProvider = services.BuildServiceProvider();

// Retrieve your resilience pipeline using the key
ResiliencePipeline pipeline = serviceProvider.GetRequiredKeyedService<ResiliencePipeline>("my-pipeline");

// Execute the pipeline
await pipelineToAdd.ExecuteAsync(static async token =>
{
    // Your custom logic goes here
});
```

Thanks @martincostello. But isn't:

```C#
ResiliencePipeline pipeline = new ResiliencePipelineBuilder().Build();
```

the same as:

 ```C#
ResiliencePipeline pipeline = ResiliencePipeline.Empty;
```

?

Is there any `ResiliencePipelineProvider` that can be used for testing that always returns an empty `ResiliencePipeline`? Would be nice to avoid creating a mock and configure it. Thinking something like this:

```C#
public class EmptyResiliencePipelineProvider : ResiliencePipelineProvider<string>
{
    public override bool TryGetPipeline(string key, [NotNullWhen(true)] out ResiliencePipeline? pipeline)
    {
        pipeline = ResiliencePipeline.Empty;

        return true;
    }

    public override bool TryGetPipeline<TResult>(string key, [NotNullWhen(true)] out ResiliencePipeline<TResult>? pipeline)
    {
        pipeline = ResiliencePipeline<TResult>.Empty;

        return true;
    }
}
```

@pekspro What we can do in Polly is something like this automatically:

``` csharp
services.AddKeyedSingleton(
    key,
    (serviceProvider, key) =>
    {
        var pipelineProvider = serviceProvider.GetRequiredService<ResiliencePipelineProvider<TKey>>();

        return pipelineProvider.GetPipeline((TKey)key!);
    });
```

Basically, whenever the `AddResiliencePipeline` is called, we can also register a keyed singleton `ResiliencePipeline`. 

Then, the following should work:

``` csharp

services.AddResiliencePipeline("my-pipeline2", builder => ... );

public class MyApi2
{
    private readonly ResiliencePipeline _pipeline;

    public MyApi2([FromKeyedServices("my-pipeline2")] ResiliencePipeline pipeline)
    {
        _pipeline = pipeline;
    }
}
```

There are couple of limitations with keyed services:

- [Deferred pipelines](https://www.pollydocs.org/advanced/dependency-injection.html#deferred-addition-of-pipelines) won't be registered as keyed singletons because we don't know what pipelines are being added at registration time. 
- [Complex pipeline keys](https://www.pollydocs.org/advanced/dependency-injection.html#complex-pipeline-keys) won't be supported. This is because the complex key is provided at access time and we can only register single keyed singleton for such key. (known when pipeline is defined)
